South Korea Stocks: Hyundai Heavy, Hyundai Motor, GS Holdings

-- B y   S a e r o m i   S h i n
-- 
2011-05-18T06:27:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-18/south-korea-stocks-hyundai-heavy-hyundai-motor-gs-holdings.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  South Korea  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close in  Seoul . The
 Kospi Index (KOSPI)  rose 33.37, or 1.6 percent, to 2,135.78, halting a
four-day retreat. It was the gauge’s biggest gain since May 2.  Automakers:  Hyundai Motor Co. (005380)  (005380 KS), South Korea’s
largest automaker, rose 5.5 percent to 238,500 won, the steepest
jump since April 28. Affiliate  Kia Motors Corp. (000270)  (000270 KS)
climbed 3.7 percent to 74,800 won. The companies advanced on
speculation May vehicle sales will be “strong,” said Chae Hee Guen, an analyst at Hyundai Securities Co.  Shipbuilders: Hyundai Heavy Industries Co. (009540 KS), the
world’s biggest shipbuilder, rose 6.6 percent to 475,000 won,
after Yonhap News reported the company won orders from Knutsen
NYK Offshore Tankers AS to build two shuttle tankers, with
options for three more. Kim Ki Young, a spokesman for Hyundai
Heavy, said he has no comment.  Other shipyards also advanced, with Daewoo Shipbuilding &
Marine Engineering Co. (042660 KS) rallying 5.3 percent to
44,050 won and Samsung Heavy Industries Co. (010140 KS) gaining
5.4 percent to 44,950 won.  GS Holdings (078930)  Corp. (078930 KS), the parent of South Korea’s
No. 2 refiner GS Caltex Corp., advanced 5.3 percent to 89,200
won, the largest gain since April 21. Credit Suisse Group AG
raised its share-price estimate to 125,000 won, citing better-
than-estimated quarterly earnings.  NCsoft Corp. (036570)  (036570 KS), a South Korean online game maker,
retreated 1.5 percent to 267,000 won, falling for a second day.
The company had its rating cut to “neutral” from
“overweight” at JPMorgan Chase & Co.  To contact the reporter on this story:
